1. These are early stats.

Here’s what happened:

1. Been running a new customer acquisition campaign for almost 3 years. Same campaign, same ad, been working well.

2. The pitch in the first upsell needed to be updated because it was showing old stats.

3. So I re-wrote it but made it 95% educational and only 5% “pitch”.

4. I also raised the price by 262%.

As you can see from the image above, the new version that’s 262% more expensive is converting better than the original.

The “trick” was just to (finally) sit my @ss down and re-do the pitch. Took maybe two hours including editing the video and all that.

Been putting it off forever.

But there’s a deeper lesson to be learned (I probably need to learn it most - which is why I’m writing this.)

I want to acquire more new customers - and that campaign I’ve been running forever hits a ceiling when I try to scale it.

Over the past year, that *one* component of the promo (it’s an upsell) has generated $53k in sales.

If the numbers hold and I get the same amount of front-end customers, it’ll bring in $138k. (Not the entire promo. Just the upsell.)

This will let me spend more on ads and get more new customers.

Instead of trying to create an entirely new front end offer and a whole new funnel, all I had to do was tweak ONE part of it.

It’s like this with almost EVERY sales process or funnel or whatever you want to call it.

Most of the time, you’ll make more by just finding the ONE part of it that needs improving …and then simply improve THAT. 

As entrepreneurs, we’re more inclined to make entirely NEW offers and funnels because we need to CREATE.

So …channel that energy into finding the ONE thing that will move the needle the most …and then fix THAT.

Oh - and test more stuff lol.

I never run split tests. It’s out of laziness. 

Don’t make that mistake. I already made it for you.

I woke up at 3:30 this morning with the complete message for the 2023 State Of The Internet Address in my head.

We make it all about US.

THERE IS NO *US* WITHOUT *THEM.*

The “them” in this case is the customer. The consumer.

To quote David Ogilvy, “The consumer is not a moron. She’s your wife.”

My friends, we are treating the consumer like a moron.

If we don’t stop, the day will come when there is no more “us”.

A few points in no particular order because I’m writing this on my phone at 5:50AM:

Our success doesn’t come from money. Our success comes from the results we get for the people who pay us.

If we put our focus there, the money comes faster, easier, and in greater abundance.

Choose your role models very carefully. The person who makes the most money isn’t necessarily right by default. 

Pablo Escobar made more than all of us combined - but we’d be fools to follow in his footsteps. 

Finally (because I’m running out of characters), what each one of us does has an effect on the entire community.

Every time a consumer is hurt - the entire community takes a hit. 

When one does bad - we ALL do bad in the eye of the consumer.

And that consumer?

Without her we are nothing.

What if you were only allowed to work for three days a week?

I have this friend Brooke and she’s militant about only working 3 days a week.

And she’s even more “strict” about the hours she works.

I think she only “allows” herself like four hours on those days too. Something like that.

What’s crazy is last I heard from her, she does over $50M a year.

She told me that having those strict “rules” makes it so the time she spends working is time spent doing *only* the most important stuff that makes the most money.

Kind of a cool way to look at it. 

I’ve been able to cut down on work time by doing this:

1. Write a journal of everything you do each day for a solid week.

2. Review it and see where you’re doing stuff that doesn’t really move the needle.

3. Stop doing that stuff.

When I did that, I learned that I spent HOURS doing something I call the “stats loop”.

I’d check email, check my stats, then check all my tech stuff to make sure my stats were accurate, and then repeat.

I learned that over the course of a day, I’d spend HOURS doing this. 

I just didn’t realize how much time I was wasting until I “logged” it in a journal.

Now I don’t do that anymore.

This has reduced my stress by a zillion percent …and it’s freed up “mental bandwidth” to discover what the best use of my time is …which is:

1. Brainstorming ways to deliver more value to my market.

2. Delivering that value through content and classes.

All of this has led to more net profit, more goodwill and impact, more fun, and less stress and anxiety.

The only “hard part” is keeping up the self discipline to not go back into the “looping” pattern.

So …maybe give it a try? 

Sure did wonders for me. Hope it helps you too :-)

P.S. I don’t work 3 days a week. I cut it down from 7 days to 5 …and cut my work hours down from 7AM-7PM to a loose schedule like this:

Early Morning: Review goals, do brain entrainment exercises, read.

Mid morning - lunch: Create & Build. (This is either making content, teaching live classes, contributing to my private groups, or building tech stuff like automations etc.)

Lunch - mid afternoon: Free time

Mid afternoon - 5 (ish): Plan & Review.

Workin’ pretty good!
